<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Description of female.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
While a detailed description of the holotype male of this species, complete with quality drawings, is provided in 
<bibRefCitation author="Krikken, J" journalOrPublisher=")" pageId="10" pageNumber="45" pagination="185 - 189" title="New cetoniine taxa from Africa and Asia (Coleoptera, Cetoniidae). Revue francaise d'Entomologie (N. S." volume="2" year="1980">Krikken (1980)</bibRefCitation>
, the female has remained unknown until the recent posting of a photo of a specimen by A. Deacon on the iSpot site. The specimen was found freshly dead on the beach of Praia do Bilene and the photo is of sufficiently high resolution to ascertain that it belongs to this sex and to recognise its key characters. On the basis of this, the female is essentially identical to the male in general appearance (Figs 1A, 2A), with the exception that it exhibits 
<pageBreakToken pageId="1" pageNumber="36" start="start">convex</pageBreakToken>
abdominal sternites without the medial vertical groove, which is typical of the male. The protibiae are also significantly broader anteriorly than in the male, and visibly tridentate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
